    seo_description: 'What to wear to an office dinner as a man. Expert advice on smart attire for work dinners, company events, and professional social evenings in Britain.',
    intro_text: 'The office dinner occupies a uniquely nuanced position in men\'s dressing: it is neither a purely formal occasion nor a fully casual one, and navigating the gap between the two requires a more considered approach than either extreme demands. Whether it is an annual company dinner, a team celebration, a client entertainment evening, or a post-promotion dinner, the office dinner carries professional implications that a purely social occasion does not. You are being observed by colleagues and, in many cases, by people who influence your career — and your appearance contributes to their overall impression of you as a professional and as someone who understands the unspoken codes of their environment.',
    style_tips: 'A well-fitted suit in navy, charcoal, or mid-grey is the most reliable choice for an office dinner; it reads as professional and well-prepared while still being appropriate for a social evening\nIf a suit feels overly formal for the specific occasion, a blazer with smart tailored trousers — not chinos — is a strong alternative that maintains a professional edge without the full formality of a matched suit\nA dress shirt in white or pale blue with a conservative tie is appropriate for most professional dinner settings; if the evening is more relaxed, an open collar can work with a quality shirt that holds its shape well\nShoe quality matters disproportionately in professional settings — well-polished black or dark brown Oxfords or derbies are always the correct choice and communicate the same attention to detail as your overall outfit\nAvoid very casual items such as jeans, trainers, or open-collar shirts without a jacket — even at the most relaxed company dinner, these can read as a lack of awareness of professional social codes\nDress slightly better than you expect others will — being the best-dressed person in the room at an office dinner is rarely a disadvantage, whereas looking underdressed can be difficult to recover from in a professional social context',
    recommended_pieces: 'Navy or charcoal single-breasted suit in a quality wool worsted\nWhite or pale blue fine cotton dress shirt\nConservative silk tie in a plain colour or subtle woven pattern\nWell-polished black or dark brown Oxford or derby shoes\nSimple pocket square and a classic watch to complete the look without ostentation',
    dos_and_donts: 'Do treat the office dinner as a professional occasion first and a social one second — the people present will form and update their views of you as a colleague and professional\nDo dress at the upper end of what you expect the dress standard to be; the professional cost of being underdressed at a company dinner is higher than the social awkwardness of being slightly overdressed\nEnsure everything is clean, pressed, and well-maintained — worn cuffs, scuffed shoes, or a loosely knotted tie communicate carelessness rather than confidence\nDon\'t dress in a manner that is dramatically different from your usual professional style — wearing a three-piece suit to a casual team dinner can feel as odd as wearing jeans to a board dinner\nAvoid very casual items even at the most relaxed company dinners; a blazer and smart shirt is the minimum that maintains a professional impression in a social work setting\nNever drink to excess at an office dinner while dressed in a way that draws attention; your outfit and your conduct together form the total impression that colleagues and senior staff will carry away from the evening',
    collection_link: '/collections/all',
